Japan's Charade Aimed at Military Supremacy under Fire 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- The Japanese government recently clarified that it would adopt a policy to regard countering "ballistic missile attack" from someone as a major goal of its "plan to protect the people".
 Commenting on this, Rodong Sinmun Monday observes that Japan's talk about "missile threat" allegedly from the DPRK is a provocation to it and the "plan to protect the people" is nothing but a fig-leaf to cover up its sinister aim. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The news analyst continues: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is an invariable ambition of the Japanese reactionaries to hold military supremacy over Northeast Asia and unfailingly realize at a proper time the old dream of the "Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere," which Japan failed to do so in the past. They attempt to contain not only the DPRK but China and Russia under the signboard of fictitious "missile attack" in a bid to ensure military supremacy. That is why they are pushing forward their moves to convert Japan into a military giant in real earnest and working hard together with the U.S. to develop and deploy the missile defense system.
 The danger of Japan's military expansion and militarism is now further increasing than ever before. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan's ambition to establish military supremacy over Northeast Asia is an anachronistic one as it leads to its second defeat. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan would be well advised to face up to the times and reality with a cool head and give up its megalomaniacal dream.

Truth about S. Korean Development of Metal Uranium Disclosed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- It has been disclosed afresh that the south Korean Atomic Energy Institute developed metal uranium for depleted uranium warheads from 1983 to 1987, creating quite a stir, south Korean KBS reported.
 This was brought to light by the Green Federation and Jo Sung Su, an assemblyman from the Democratic Workers' Party, at a joint press conference at the National Assembly on Oct. 21. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They said the south Korean Atomic Energy Institute in 1982 converted depleted uranium imported from the United States into hundreds of kilograms of metal uranium for anti-tank gun warheads with the help of the Defense Science Institute. They testified that the U.S. intelligence organ had been informed of this fact. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The true colors of those who have created a nuclear crisis on the Korean Peninsula have been brought into daylight with the successive exposure of the nuclear arms development in south Korea and the criminal acts of the United States in conniving at and encouraging it.

DPRK's Stand on Peaceful Use of Space Clarified 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- The space, the common heritage of humankind, must be used under all circumstances for the wellbeing of the peoples of all countries, urged the DPRK delegate in his speech in the discussion of the agenda "International Cooperation in Peaceful Use of Outer Space" at the Fourth Committee of the 59th UN General Assembly on Oct. 18.
 Making clear the principled stand of the DPRK in this regard, he said: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Firstly, the member nations should take a joint action against the militarization of the space. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Espionage and war equipment continues to be deployed in the space and many spy satellites are carrying on espionage on other countries. The Missile Defense System will result in expanding military confrontation and arms race to the space and obstructing the peaceful development and use of the space. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK delegation denounces all the acts to militarize the space and hold that an international legal system and a preventive mechanism to check the militarization of the space should be established amid the concern of all the UN member nations and by their efforts. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Secondly, all the countries should be allowed to freely participate in the peaceful development and use of the space on an equal footing. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Attempts to obstruct the space development of developing countries for the maintenance of technological priority and to monopolize it should be strictly rejected. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  The activities of developing countries to develop the space should be encouraged as the space is a common property of all countries and nations, though there may be technological differences between advanced and backward countries in the development of the space. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 And it is important to make the achievements registered in space development a common property for the wellbeing of all countries and peoples. To this end, all the space plans worked out by the UN should give priority to helping the developing countries and the developed countries should sincerely share the space technology and achievements with the developing countries. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK will further develop space science and technology and actively promote cooperation and exchange with the United Nations and various countries of the world in the peaceful use of the space.

Letter to Kim Jong Il from Participants in International Meeting 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- Leader Kim Jong Il received a letter from the participants in the international meeting for peace and reunification of Korea in Lima.
 The letter says: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At the international meeting we analyzed and discussed the root cause of the Korean Peninsula being the most acute hotspot in the world and reached the consensus of view that the responsibility for the tensions created on the Korean Peninsula entirely rests with the malicious hostile policy of the United States toward the DPRK and vowed to invigorate the struggle against the U.S. imperialists' moves to isolate and stifle the DPRK for the sake of peace in Asia and the rest of the world. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. has pursued all along war and division, illegally occupying south Korea for nearly 60 years since the Second World War. It gave rise to the nuclear issue, the focal point of the DPRK-U.S. confrontation, by its persistent moves to isolate and stifle the DPRK and is shameless enough to brand the DPRK as "a nuclear criminal." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Worse still, in recent years, the U.S. has massively shipped ultra-modern military hardware into south Korea and staged war games under various names, presenting military threat and blackmail to the DPRK, while misleading world opinion and whipping up hostile feelings toward the DPRK by pulling it up over the fictitious "human rights problem." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Facts show that the Korean issue cannot be settled without a change in the U.S. hostile policy toward the DPRK and that peace cannot be preserved on the Korean Peninsula, not to speak of its reunification, without a tough countermeasure to cope with the U.S. "doctrine of strength." 
 It is only too legitimate right of the Korean people to build up their self-defensive and peaceable force to counterbalance the U.S. harebrained racket for nuclear confrontation and military pressure. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Respected Your Excellency Kim Jong Il are overwhelming the reckless strong-arm and arbitrary practices and new war provocation moves of the U.S. and firmly defending the sovereignty and vital rights of the Korean people with your outstanding Songun policy. This is not only great exploits in defending peace on the Korean Peninsula but also a significant contribution to the peace of the world and the cause of independence of the international community. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 We will expose and condemn the injustice of the U.S. dominationism and moves to isolate and stifle the DPRK and arouse support and encouragement of broad global community to the just struggle of the Korean people and thus always remain on the side of your people in the righteous struggle to ensure a lasting peace on the Korean Peninsula and reunify divided Korea.

S. Korea Urged to Withdraw Troops from Iraq 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- South Korea is seized with uneasiness and horror after international terrorist organization Al Qaeda declared that it would mount an indiscriminate attack on south Korea for having dispatched combat troops to Iraq.
 Blaming the U.S., a terrorist kingpin, for the threat of terrorist attack posed to south Korea, a signed commentary of Rodong Sinmun Monday observes that had the U.S. not launched the war of aggression against Iraq, a sovereign state, and pressurized the south Korean authorities to dispatch troops to Iraq, south Korea would not have been listed as a target of terrorist attack and exposed to the present threat. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Noting that young and middle-aged south Koreans were hurled into Iraq as bullet shields under the pressure of the U.S. and south Korea is accused of being fighting a proxy war and collaborating with the U.S. in its war of aggression, the commentary goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The south Korean authorities can never evade the responsibility for the present disturbing development as they sent troops to Iraq, yielding to the U.S. brigandish demand despite people's strong opposition to it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The only way for south Korea to get rid of terror-phobia is not to increase security alert or to take a measure to prohibit entry of suspects into it but to withdraw its troops from Iraq without delay and stop supporting the U.S. in the implementation of its policy for a war of aggression. This would be beneficial to south Korea as this is urgently required by the times and people. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The south Korean authorities should clearly face up to the reality today when the people's life and security are seriously threatened, stop reading the face of outsiders and take a bold decision to pull back their troops from Iraq.

Anniversary of CPV's Entry into Korean Front Observed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- The exploits performed by the fighters of the Chinese People's Volunteers (CPV) in the great Fatherland Liberation War of the Korean people will shine long along with the history of DPRK-China friendship, says Rodong Sinmun Monday in a signed article dedicated to the 54th anniversary of the CPV's entry into the Korean front.
 It says: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The party and government of China dispatched the CPV made up of fine sons and daughters of the Chinese people to the Korean front under the uplifted banner of "Resisting America and aiding Korea, safeguarding the home and defending the motherland". &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They fought heroic decisive battles against the common enemy in the same trench with the Korean soldiers. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They bravely stormed into enemy's positions at the risk of their lives despite a hail of bullets and bombs, thus mowing down aggressors and defending heights of Korea at the cost of blood. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The heights and mountains of Korea are associated with the blood and feats of the CPV fighters. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The unparalleled bravery and collective heroism displayed by the CPV on the Korean front greatly contributed to bringing earlier the victory of the Korean army and people in the war. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Korean army and people always remember the disinterested material and moral support given by the Chinese people to them and the exploits performed by the CPV in the war. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK-China friendship has reached a higher stage in the new century. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Chinese people's support and solidarity to the revolutionary cause of the Korean people are encouraging them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Boosting the DPRK-China friendly relations fully conforms with the desire and interests of the two peoples. The DPRK-China friendly bonds will grow stronger in the future thanks to the joint efforts of the two parties, governments and peoples.

Unique Tombs of Koguryo 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- Many tombs belonging to the period of Koguryo have been unearthed in various places of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea including Mt. Ryongak and Rakrang district, Pyongyang.
 They vividly show the highly developed architecture of Koguryo and various shapes of tomb inherent in Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Koguryo people used to hold large funeral services. Theirs are piled stone tombs and mounded tombs with stone chambers. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They are developed shapes of tomb belonging to Kojoson (ancient Korea) such as dolmen, stone coffin and stone heap. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The oldest stone tombs were piled with rugged stones on the ground. But later, tombs were built with trimmed stones in the form of steps. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Typical of piled stone tombs are those of a general and a king of Koguryo in Jian, Jilin Province, China. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The general's tomb is a seven-storied platform piled up with trimmed granite stones. The coffin chamber is between the fourth and fifth stories. 
The tomb is 34 meters long and 14.3 meters high, which resembles a big structure. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The mounded tomb with a stone chamber is a developed form of piled stone tomb. Its coffin chamber was made with stones and then mounded with earth. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
The tomb has a corridor and one or two chambers or more. Nearly a hundred tombs of this shape have been discovered. Some of them have mural paintings. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Typical of them are King Tongmyong's mausoleum, Anak tomb No. 3, the three tombs in Kangso and the tomb in Tokhung-ri in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 These tombs are precious cultural assets indicative of the originality of the Koguryo culture.

Book "Concealed Aspects of U.S.-Japanese Relationship" Published in DPRK 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- The Social Sciences Publishing House has published a new book "Concealed Aspects of U.S.-Japan Relationship."
 The book consists of five chapters and a preface. It is based on facts showing the ties between the United States and Japan in all fields, political, economic and military, from the end of World War II (August 1945) to recent years. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The first chapter deals with the postwar situation of Japan, the U.S. policy of aggression on Asia, the Japan's stand towards the policy and the violation of the Potsdam Declaration by them. The second and fourth chapters disclose how the subordinate alliance and relationship of military cooperation were established between the U.S. and Japan. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The third and fifth chapters dwell on the contradictions between them and their relationship following the end of the Cold War. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In particular, the fifth chapter introduces facts revealing that the two countries had cooperated with each other for the same purpose of aggression on Asia though they had contradiction and friction in the economic, political and military fields.

KCNA Assails Projected Joint Naval Exercise
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- The United States plans to stage a joint naval exercise in waters off Japan from Oct. 26, pursuant to the Proliferation Security Initiative (PSI) by letting the Japanese reactionaries come to the fore.
 Through this the U.S. seeks to plug countries around Japan into the exercise in a bid to step up its operation to isolate and stifle the DPRK and consolidate "international cooperation" against it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Given the objective of the PSI to isolate and blockade the DPRK, it is quite clear that the exercise is designed to lay a siege to the DPRK and stifle it come what may. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 After working out the PSI whose major aim is to intercept ships and airplanes, the U.S. has staged 10 joint naval exercises under simulated conditions of an actual operation by mobilizing troops of its allies. It has put the exercises on a regular basis under the pretext of "combating the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction (WMD)." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. has pursued the strategy to isolate and stifle the DPRK, asserting that the international community is entitled to intercept ships and planes suspected of spreading weapons in the open seas and along international air routes after advancing a weapons proliferation prevention security initiative and a principle to intercept WMD last year. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This is a serious infringement upon the sovereignty of the DPRK and an intolerable military provocation to it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
The U.S. is pushing the strategy of international blockade to the phase of its implementation. A very dangerous situation is prevailing on the Korean Peninsula at present due to its reckless military moves to stifle the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The projected exercise assumes a very serious nature as it is slated to take place against the backdrop of growing tensions on the peninsula. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 U.S. massive redeployment of forces and madcap arms buildup are going on the Korean Peninsula and other parts of the Asia-Pacific region as evidenced by the deployment of Aegis destroyers of the U.S. 7th fleet equipped with up-to-date missile system in the East Sea of Korea which have already begun performing their operational duties for an actual war. The projected exercise can not be viewed as something not related to these moves. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK has warned more than once that naval blockade exercises targeted against it would not be favorable for the atmosphere of dialogue. The U.S. ceaseless military maneuvers of this form go to clearly prove that it does not stand for a peaceful settlement of the nuclear issue between the DPRK and the U.S. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The projected exercise only betrays the U.S. stand of denying dialogue and harassing peace. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is so shameless as to completely deny its dialogue partner and put pressure upon it while openly pressing for the PSI exercises to blockade and stifle the DPRK behind the scene of dialogue and threatening to bring up the nuclear issue for discussion at the UN Security Council. These moves only make the prospect of the negotiations with it dimmer as the days go by. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Dialogue can never go together with war exercises. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. seeks to escalate tension on the Korean Peninsula instead of working for peace in Northeast Asia including the peninsula. The planned exercise indicates that the U.S. strategy to militarily blockade and stifle the DPRK is inching close to the phase of its full implementation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK can not but call into question Japan, the host of the joint naval exercises, and other participants. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is, in fact, illegal and serious infringement upon the sovereignty of other countries defying international law and norms of mutual relations between countries to participate in such exercises aimed to intercept vessels of sovereign countries. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 For the Japanese authorities to host the exercises targeted against the DPRK, pursuant to the U.S. policy to isolate and blockade the DPRK, diametrically runs counter to the spirit of the DPRK-Japan Pyongyang Declaration. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is foolish an act for some countries to support and participate in the exercises which are little short of an open infringement upon the sovereignty of independent countries, pursuant to the U.S. unilateral and self-justified strategy for hegemony. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK is compelled to serve a serious warning to the U.S., regarding the exercise as a move to implement the U.S. preemptive interception strategy aimed to isolate and stifle the DPRK internationally and an ultimate war action. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Now that the U.S. has become more undisguised in its hostile policy toward the DPRK despite its repeated warnings, the latter is left with no option but to increase its physical deterrent force in every way. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the U.S. seeks to wrest a sort of concession from the DPRK through military threat and blackmail, this will only betray its total ignorance of its rival. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. had better stop running wild, clearly understanding the will of the army and people of the DPRK to return fire for fire and react to the hard-line policy with the toughest stand.

Kim Yong Nam Meets Mozambican Government Delegation
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- Kim Yong Nam, president of the Presidium of the Supreme People's Assembly of the DPRK, met and had a friendly talk with a government delegation of the Republic of Mozambique led by Leonardo Santos Simao, minister of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation, at the Mansudae Assembly Hall on Monday.
 On hand were Vice-minister of Foreign Affairs Choe Su Hon and officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At the meeting the head of the delegation said that President Joaquim Alberto Chissano requested him to convey during his visit to the DPRK the hope that the Korean people would make greater success in their struggle to shatter the U.S. blockade. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He added that the visit provided him with an opportunity to know better about the achievements made by the Korean people under wise leadership of Kim Jong Il.

Kim Yong Nam Meets Chinese Technical Delegation
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- Kim Yong Nam, president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, visited the construction site of the Taean Friendship Glass Factory on Monday and met with a technical delegation of China led by the general manager of the China Yao Hua Glass Co. Ltd.
 On hand were Kwak Pom Gi, vice-premier of the Cabinet, Jo Yun Hui, minister of Construction and Building-Materials Industries, Rim Kyong Man, minister of Foreign Trade, Kim Yong Il, vice-minister of Foreign Affairs, and officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Guan Huabing, charge d' affaires a.i., and officials of the Chinese embassy were on hand. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 After acquainting himself with the progress in the construction of the glass factory, Kim Yong Nam had a talk with them. 
 He expressed thanks to the party and the government of China for showing deep concern for the construction of the factory and gave a pep talk to the Chinese technicians in their energetic efforts to successfully complete the factory as scheduled as one of the best symbols of the DPRK-China friendship.

Wreaths Laid before Friendship Tower
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- Wreaths were laid before the Friendship Tower today on the occasion of the 54th anniversary of the Chinese People's Volunteers' entry into the Korean front.
 Present at the wreath-laying ceremony were Kim Yun Hyok, secretary general of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, Jong Chang Ryol, vice-minister of the People's Armed Forces, Kim Yong Il, vice-minister of Foreign Affairs, Kim Yong Jae, vice-minister of Foreign Trade, Jon Yong Jin, vice-chairman of the Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries, who is vice-chairman of the Central Committee of the DPRK-China Friendship Association, and officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On hand were Guan Huabing, charge d' affaires ad interim of Chinese embassy here, and staff members of the embassy. 
 Honor guards of the Korean People's Army lined up there. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Amidst the playing of the wreath-laying music, a wreath was laid there in the joint name of the Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea, the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly and the DPRK Cabinet. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Also placed there were wreaths in the names of the ministries of the People's Armed Forces, Foreign Affairs, Peoples' Security, Foreign Trade and Culture, in the joint name of the Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries and the Central Committee of the DPRK-China Friendship Association and in the joint name of the Pyongyang City Committee of the WPK and the Pyongyang City People's Committee. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Working people in the city paid floral tribute to the tower. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants observed a moment's silence in memory of the martyrs of the CPV who fell while courageously fighting on the Korean front. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On the same day wreaths were laid at the cemetery of fallen fighters of the CPV in Hyongjesan District, Pyongyang, by the Pyongyang City Committee of the WPK, the Pyongyang City People's Committee, the Hyongjesan District, Pyongyang, Committee of the WPK, the Hyongjesan District People's Committee and units of the Korean People's Army. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Meanwhile, wreaths were also laid at their cemeteries in Hoechang, Kaesong and Onsong. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 That day the Chinese embassy here and the Central Committee of the Chinese Residents Association in the DPRK placed wreaths before the tower and at the cemetery of fallen fighters of the CPV in Hyongjesan district, Pyongyang. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Meanwhile the Chinese Consulate General in Chongjin laid a wreath at the cemetery of fallen fighters of CPV in Onsong, North Hamgyong Province.

Minutes of Talks between DPRK and Mozambican For. Ministers Signed
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 25 (KCNA) -- Minutes of the talks held between the foreign minister of the DPRK and the minister of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation of Mozambique were signed here Monday.
 Pointing to the fact that the bilateral relations of cooperation are developing between the DPRK and Mozambique, the minutes underlined the need to readjust the legal framework for cooperation in economic, scientific and technological and cultural fields between the two countries to suit the new environment, steadily consolidate the traditional friendly and cooperative relations and solidarity between the two countries and expand the relations of cooperation in new fields. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It was also noted in the document that the two countries will jointly mark the 30th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations between the two countries in June, 2005. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present at the signing ceremony were Foreign Minister Paek Nam Sun and officials concerned from the DPRK side and members of the Mozambican government delegation led by Minister of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation Leonardo Santos Simao from the Mozambican side. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The ministers signed the minutes.
